---
import Base from "@/layouts/Base.astro";
import slideShip from "@/data/common-slides/pirate-ship.jpeg";
import slideFreedomTech from "@/data/common-slides/surveillance-capitalism.jpeg";
import slideWalk from "@/data/common-slides/walking.jpeg";
import slideEndurance from "@/data/common-slides/endurance.jpeg";
import slideExplorers from "@/data/common-slides/pirate-ship-2.jpeg";
import slideInPerson from "@/data/common-slides/soveng-shirt.jpeg";
import slideBias from "@/data/common-slides/show-talk-build-loop.jpeg";
import slideCypherpunks from "@/data/common-slides/cypherpunks-write-code.jpeg";
---

<Base
  title="Philosophy"
  meta_title="PHILOSOPHY"
  description="Our philosophy and principles"
>
  <section class="section-sm">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="row justify-center">
        <div class="text-center md:col-10 lg:col-7">
          <h2 class="h3 mb-6">Philosophy</h2>
          <blockquote class="italic mb-3 pl-2 bg-transparent rounded-none text-gray-200">&ldquo;If you want to build a ship, don't drum up the men to gather wood, divide the work, and give orders. Instead, teach them to yearn for the vast and endless sea.&rdquo; &mdash;Antoine de&nbsp;Saint-Exupéry</blockquote>
          <figure class="my-8 md:float-left md:mr-6 md:w-1/2">
            <img src={slideShip.src} alt="Yearn for the vast and endless sea" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg" loading="lazy" />
          </figure>
          <div class="content text-left">
            <p>Sovereign Engineering is grounded in the values embodied by Bitcoin: <strong>self-sovereignty, agency, and censorship-resistance</strong>. We build technology that maximises individual freedom, minimises reliance on trusted third parties, and treats the individual as the ultimate node in every network.</p>
            <p>From <a href="https://njump.me/nevent1qqsqm2lz4ru6wlydzpulgs8m60ylp4vufwsg55whlqgua6a93vp2y4gpzamhxue69uhhyetvv9ujuer9wfnkjemf9e3k7mgzyphydppzm7m554ecwq4gsgaek2qk32atse2l4t9ks57dpms4mmhfxjc476g" target="_blank" rel="noopener">"Fix the Money, Fix the Web"</a> we take the conviction that a sound monetary foundation is a moral imperative, and that Bitcoin's paradigm of extreme ownership demands equally sovereign applications. Likewise, <a href="https://sovereignengineering.io/nostr.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Nostr</a> reminds us that protocols, not platforms, will reclaim the vibrant, open experimentation that defined the early web.</p>

            <h3 class="h4 clear-both mt-16 mb-4">Freedom by Design</h3>
            <blockquote class="italic mb-3 pl-2 bg-transparent rounded-none text-gray-200">&ldquo;Freedom Tech is rug-pull-resistant technology.&rdquo; <cite class="not-italic font-normal text-gray-400 text-sm ml-2">&mdash;Gigi</cite></blockquote>
            <figure class="my-8 md:float-right md:ml-6 md:w-1/2">
              <img src={slideFreedomTech.src} alt="Freedom Tech slide" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg" loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <p>Bitcoin, Lightning, and Nostr prove that code can embed freedom at the protocol layer: freedom of speech, assembly, movement, and of course financial freedom.  We strive to reproduce that super-power in every system we touch, so that liberty is enforced by mathematics rather than maintained by promises.</p>
            <p>Good design begins with values.  We minimise dependencies, maximise verifiability, and keep exit-costs asymptotically close to zero. When the design is right, freedom is a property—not a permission.</p>
            <p>This way of thinking is what we call <em>Freedom Tech</em>: technology that is rug-pull-resistant by design.  When betrayal is impossible, trust becomes optional and collaboration scales.</p>

            <h3 class="h4 clear-both mt-16 mb-4">Distributed Cognition</h3>
            <blockquote class="italic mb-3 pl-2 bg-transparent rounded-none text-gray-200">&ldquo;Solvitur ambulando.&rdquo; <cite class="not-italic font-normal text-gray-400 text-sm ml-2">&mdash;Saint&nbsp;Augustine</cite></blockquote>
            <figure class="my-8 md:float-left md:mr-6 md:w-1/2">
              <img src={slideWalk.src} alt="Walk & Talk slide" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg" loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <p>No ill-defined problem was ever solved in isolation.  By gathering bright minds in a high-trust setting we tap into what cognitive scientist John&nbsp;Vervaeke calls <em>distributed cognition</em>.  Ideas bounce, mutate, and compound until entirely new solution-spaces appear.</p>
            <p>The fuel for that process is conversation, and the best conversations happen while <em>walking</em>.  Saint&nbsp;Augustine called it <em>Solvitur ambulando</em>—"by walking it shall be solved." Madeira's levadas offer kilometres of cognitive runway.</p>
            <p>Friday's Demo Day then serves as an epistemic checkpoint.  Six minutes to show, two to discuss.  Brutal, illuminating, and endlessly inspiring.</p>

            <h3 class="h4 clear-both mt-16 mb-4">Explorers of a New Frontier</h3>
            <blockquote class="italic mb-3 pl-2 bg-transparent rounded-none text-gray-200">&ldquo;Re-invent the future.&rdquo; <cite class="not-italic font-normal text-gray-400 text-sm ml-2">&mdash;Bell&nbsp;Labs</cite></blockquote>
            <figure class="my-8 md:float-right md:ml-6 md:w-1/2">
              <img src={slideExplorers.src} alt="Exploring the digital ocean" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg" loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <p>Our logo is a ship for a reason. Bitcoin and Nostr open a digital ocean as uncharted as the Age of Discovery. We welcome builders who yearn for that &ldquo;wild and open sea,&rdquo; who embrace risk, and who delight in charting new waters.</p>
            <p>Like Shackleton's crew, participants must trust one another when storms hit, and celebrate together when new land appears on the horizon. The sea is vast, and so is the opportunity.</p>
            <p>Those who prefer calm harbours and predictable schedules need not apply.  We are optimised for the pirates, the adventurers, and the stubborn optimists who believe the internet can still astonish us.</p>

            <h3 class="h4 clear-both mt-16 mb-4">In-Person, High-Bandwidth</h3>
            <blockquote class="italic mb-3 pl-2 bg-transparent rounded-none text-gray-200">&ldquo;If you want to go fast, go alone. If you want to go far, go together.&rdquo; <cite class="not-italic font-normal text-gray-400 text-sm ml-2">&mdash;African&nbsp;Proverb</cite></blockquote>
            <figure class="my-8 md:float-left md:mr-6 md:w-1/2">
              <img src={slideInPerson.src} alt="Cohort collaboration" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg" loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <p>The magic happens face-to-face. Six weeks of shared meals, shared walks, and shared victories forge bonds that bandwidth-limited Zoom calls simply cannot replicate. Trust is built in the queue for poncha, not in a Discord channel.</p>
            <p>Madeira's Bitcoin-friendly ecosystem (see the <a href="https://btcmap.org/community/free-madeira" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BTCMap</a> or visit <a href="https://freemadeira.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FREE&nbsp;Madeira</a>) provides the perfect real-world playground to test ideas minutes after they compile.</p>
            <p>Prototype on Monday, spend it on Tuesday, iterate by Friday.  That feedback loop is only possible when hardware, merchants, and curious peers live within walking distance.</p>

            <h3 class="h4 clear-both mt-16 mb-4">Bias for Action</h3>
            <blockquote class="italic mb-3 pl-2 bg-transparent rounded-none text-gray-200">&ldquo;Direction is so much more important than speed. Many are going nowhere fast.&rdquo; <cite class="not-italic font-normal text-gray-400 text-sm ml-2">&mdash;Unknown</cite></blockquote>
            <figure class="my-8 md:float-right md:ml-6 md:w-1/2">
              <img src={slideBias.src} alt="Show-Talk-Build loop" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg" loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <p>We prototype first, critique later. Imperfect code is welcomed if it advances the conversation. Novelty, experimentation, and rapid iteration trump premature optimisation.</p>
            <p>This bias for action produces tangible results: from <em>Blossom</em> to <em>ZapStore</em>, many cohort projects were conceived on a Monday walk and open-sourced before the next weekend. The world needs working code, not slide decks.</p>
            <p>Direction beats speed, yet speed still helps.  We chase the 80-20, knowing that the last 20 % can wait until the idea survives first contact with reality.</p>

            <h3 class="h4 clear-both mt-16 mb-4">Build&nbsp;It&nbsp;Right</h3>
            <blockquote class="italic mb-3 pl-2 bg-transparent rounded-none text-gray-200">&ldquo;The computer can be used as a tool to liberate and protect people, rather than to control them.&rdquo; <cite class="not-italic font-normal text-gray-400 text-sm ml-2">&mdash;Hal&nbsp;Finney</cite></blockquote>
            <figure class="my-8 md:float-left md:mr-6 md:w-1/2">
              <img src={slideCypherpunks.src} alt="Cypherpunks write code" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg" loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <p class="mb-4"><em>&ldquo;What does it mean to &#39;build it right?&#39;&rdquo;</em> ask Pablo&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Gigi. It means writing code that the user can verify, fork, and <em>exit</em> from; choosing architectures that minimise trust; and favouring primitives that stand the test of decades.</p>
            <p>Hal&nbsp;Finney's challenge calls for code that stands on its own—transparent, user-verifiable, and resilient to adversarial pressure.  We prize lean binaries, readable source, and simple dependency graphs so every sailor on this digital ocean can audit the hull before they board.</p>
            <h3 class="h4 clear-both mt-16 mb-4">No&nbsp;Solutions</h3>
            <blockquote class="italic mb-3 pl-2 bg-transparent rounded-none text-gray-200">&ldquo;No solutions, only trade-offs.&rdquo; <cite class="not-italic font-normal text-gray-400 text-sm ml-2">&mdash;Thomas&nbsp;Sowell</cite></blockquote>
            <p>Our craft is the art of choosing the right compromises—those that maximise sovereignty, minimise trust, and preserve optionality for generations of builders to come.</p>
            <p>We unpack trade-offs every week on the <a href="https://castr.me/npub1n00yy9y3704drtpph5wszen64w287nquftkcwcjv7gnnkpk2q54s73000n" target="_blank" rel="noopener">No&nbsp;Solutions&nbsp;podcast</a>&nbsp;—a running dialogue on hard problems, half-baked ideas, and the messy path from concept to code.</p>

            <h3 class="h4 clear-both mt-16 mb-4">Endurance</h3>
            <blockquote class="italic mb-3 pl-2 bg-transparent rounded-none text-gray-200">&ldquo;Fortitudine vincimus.&rdquo; <cite class="not-italic font-normal text-gray-400 text-sm ml-2">&mdash;Ernest&nbsp;Shackleton</cite></blockquote>
            <figure class="my-8 md:float-right md:ml-6 md:w-1/2">
              <img src={slideEndurance.src} alt="Endurance slide" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg" loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <p>Building sovereign systems is a <strong>marathon</strong>, not a sprint; endurance and steady iteration win the day.</p>
            <p>Freedom Tech is not built in fiscal quarters; it is forged across decades.  We favour antifragile tooling, small teams, and battle-tested primitives that will still compile when our grandchildren fork the repo.</p>
            <p>We endure because the mission matters: <strong>fix the money, fix the internet</strong>.  Everything else is a footnote.</p>

            <div class="text-center mt-20">
              <a href="/apply" class="btn-retro">Apply&nbsp;Now</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base> 